\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Probabilistically Perfect Cloning of Two Pure States: A Geometric Approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
V.
 Yerokhin
\begin_inset Formula $^{1}$
\end_inset

, A.
 Shehu
\begin_inset Formula $^{1}$
\end_inset

, E.
 Feldman
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

, E.
 Bagan
\begin_inset Formula $^{1,3}$
\end_inset

 and J.
 A.
 Bergou
\begin_inset Formula $^{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Affiliation
\begin_inset Formula $^{1}$
\end_inset

Department of Physics and Astronomy, Hunter College of the City University
 of New York, 695 Park Avenue, New York, NY 10065, USA
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

Department of Mathematics, Graduate Center of the City University of New
 York, 365 Fifth Avenue, New York, New York 10016, USA 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

Física Teòrica: Informació i Fenòmens Quàntics, Universitat Autònoma de
 Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra (Barcelona), Spain 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
We solve the long-standing problem of making 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 perfect clones from 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 copies of one of two known pure states with minimum failure probability
 in the general case where the known states have arbitrary a-priori probabilitie
s.
 The solution emerges from a geometric formulation of the problem.
 This formulation also reveals a deeper connection between cloning and state
 discrimination.
 The convergence of cloning to state discrimination as the number of clones
 goes to infinity exhibits a phenomenon analogous to a second order phase
 transition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout PACS
03.67.-a, 03.65.Ta,42.50.-p 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is impossible to always clone quantum states perfectly 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Herbert, Wooters, Dieks"

\end_inset

.
 This leads to advantages for quantum systems over classical ones in some
 communications protocols of practical relevance.
 A common example is stronger security in cryptographic key distribution,
 with recent works showing more applications
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pomarico, Bart"

\end_inset

.
 Developments in cloning, including probabilistically perfect 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DuanGuo"

\end_inset

 and approximate cloning
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gisin1,Buzek,Brub,Chefles1,Fiurasek"

\end_inset

 provide anchors for better understanding quantum theory as a whole, such
 as the relationship between the no-cloning and no-signaling theorems
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Barnum"

\end_inset

, and fundamental limits on quantum measurements
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chiribella,Bae,Chiribella2006,Gendra"

\end_inset

.
 In particular, cloning's relationship with the fundamental limits of state
 discrimination will be central to this Letter.
 For reviews citing recent developments, applications and experiments see
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "review1,Fan"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When knowledge of the states' preparation is available, perfect cloning
 is probabilistically possible.
 With the first result in probabilistic cloning, Duan and Guo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DuanGuo"

\end_inset

 considered the problem of producing perfect clones of linearly-independent
 pure states and focused on the two state case.
 They found the maximum average success rate when both states are equally
 likely, and set this success probability as an upper bound for arbitrary
 prior probabilities.
 While other work has been done on this problem, there has until now been
 no general solution.
 In this
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Letter we obtain the general analytic solution and use this to examine cloning's
 relationship with state discrimination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are a number of reasons why one might want to solve the general problem
 with arbitrary a-priori probabilities.
 (i)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The solution to the equal prior problem is obtained using only symmetry
 arguments, with no need for optimization.
 (ii)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A general solution would check the robustness of the equal priors case against
 variations of the prior probabilities around 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

.
 This gives control over errors that are unavoidable for any physical realizatio
n.
 (iii)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

One could consider a discrimination protocol consisting of optimal cloning
 followed by optimal Unambiguous Discrimination (UD) of the produced clones,
 which we will call discrimination by cloning.
 Surprisingly this is optimal for equal a-priori probabilities and for any
 number of clones (see below).
 This suggests that the equal-priors case is very special and can provide
 a deceptive view of cloning.
 (iv)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In the limit of infinitely many clones, the optimal strategy prepares the
 clones according to the outcomes of UD of the input states.
 This is a particular case of a measure and prepare protocol, which we will
 call cloning by discrimination.
 Since the UD measurement varies over the range of prior probabilities (a
 3-outcome generalized measurement vs a 2-outcome projective measurement),
 this hints at a similar situation for optimal cloning that can only be
 revealed by solving the general problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our solution shows that discrimination by cloning as outlined in (iii) is
 sub-optimal for unequal prior probabilities (unless one state is never
 sent).
 This indicates that the equal prior case is not representative of state
 dependent cloning.
 Additionally, contrary to the suggestions in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(iv) above, our solution leads to a failure probability that is a smooth
 function of the priors.
 However, the strategy converges to cloning by discrimination as
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, implying a discontinuous second derivative and revealing a phenomenon
 similar to a second order phase transition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can imagine a state dependent probabilistic cloner as a machine with
 an input port, an output port and two flags that herald the success or
 failure of cloning.
 The input 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}^{m}\rangle=|\psi_{i}\rangle^{\otimes m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 identical copies of either 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

) is fed through the input port for processing.
 In case of success 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 perfect clones
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}^{n}\rangle=|\psi_{i}\rangle^{\otimes n}$
\end_inset

 are delivered through the output port with conditioned probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, the output is in a refuse state.
 Conditioned to the input state being 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{i}^{m}\rangle$
\end_inset

, the failure probability is
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}=1-p_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For cloning, optimality is usually addressed from a Bayesian viewpoint that
 assumes the states to be cloned are given with some a-priori probabilities
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then a natural cost function for our probabilistic machines is given by
 the averaged failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}.\label{obj fun}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Accordingly, the optimal cloner minimizes the cost function 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Accordingly, the optimal cloner is one that minimizes the cost function
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Our aim is to find that optimal cloner and the minimum average failure
 probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 for arbitrary priors 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%The cloning process can be thought of as a generalized measurement and
 can be described by two operators~
\backslash
mbox{$A_{
\backslash
rm succ}$, $A_{
\backslash
rm fail}$}, so that~$A^
\backslash
dagger{}_{
\backslash
kern-.3em
\backslash
rm succ}A_{
\backslash
rm succ}+A^
\backslash
dagger{}_{
\backslash
kern-.2em
\backslash
rm fail}A_{
\backslash
rm fail}=
\backslash
openone$.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%However, Neumark's theorem~
\backslash
cite{Bergou} provides an alternative approach  that turns out to be more
 convenient for our analysis.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our formulation, similar to that in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DuanGuo"

\end_inset

, the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes m}$
\end_inset

 of the original 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 copies is supplemented by an ancillary space
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula ${\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes(n-m)}\otimes{\mathscr{H}}_{F}$
\end_inset

 that accommodates both the additional 
\begin_inset Formula $n-m$
\end_inset

 clones as well as the success/failure flags.
 Then, a unitary transformation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 (time evolution) from 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes m}\otimes{\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes(n-m)}\otimes{\mathscr{H}}_{F}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes n}\otimes{\mathscr{H}}_{F}$
\end_inset

 is defined through
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DuanGuo"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U|\psi_{i}^{m}\rangle|0\rangle=\sqrt{p_{i}}|\psi_{i}^{n}\rangle|\alpha_{i}\rangle+\sqrt{q}_{i}|\Phi\rangle,\quad i=1,2.\label{Ui}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here the ancillas are initialized in a reference state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ke0$
\end_inset

.
 The states of the flag associated with successful cloning
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ke{\alpha_{i}}$
\end_inset

 are constrained to be orthogonal to the refuse state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ke{\Phi}$
\end_inset

 for certainty in the outcomes of the projective measurement on the flag
 space 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathscr{H}}_{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Although for optimal cloning 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{1}\rangle=|\alpha_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, we need to consider a more general setup where these two states are different
 to include the cloning-by-discrimination protocol whereby UD is used to
 identify the input state and then the clones are prepared accordingly
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Likewise, we could consider a more general setup with two refuse states
 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Ui"

\end_inset

).
 This is necessarily sub-optimal since we could probabilistically determine
 whether we received 
\begin_inset Formula $\ke{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\ke{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 by applying UD to the refuse states 
\begin_inset Formula $\ke{\Phi_{i}}$
\end_inset

.
 Sometimes we would be certain of the input state, when we can always prepare
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 copies of the state, thereby increasing the overall success rate of the
 cloning strategy.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For UD the success flag states must be distinguishable, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\alpha_{1}|\alpha_{2}\rangle=0$
\end_inset

.
 Taking the inner product of each equation with itself shows that our probabilit
ies are normalized: 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}+q_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, by taking the product of the two equations in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Ui"

\end_inset

), we find the unitarity constraint 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s^{m}=\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}\,s^{n}\alpha+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}},\label{unit cond}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the overlaps 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\bk{\psi_{1}}{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\langle\alpha_{1}|\alpha_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

 can be chosen to be real valued without any loss of generality.
 Furthermore, we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le s\le1$
\end_inset

.
 We note that for optimal cloning one has
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

, whereas
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 for cloning by discrimination.
 If Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) is satisfied, it is not hard to prove that
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 has a unitary extension on the whole space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% ${
\backslash
mathscr H}^{
\backslash
otimes n}
\backslash
otimes{
\backslash
mathscr H}_F$.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

