\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and its normal vector
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1},\eta_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Plotted for 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0.8,0,-0.8$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:1"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before attempting to minimize 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, we need to gain geometric insight into the meaning of the unitary constraint.
 The following points turn out to be important: (a)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) defines a class of smooth curves on the unit square 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le q_{i}\le1$
\end_inset

 (e.g., solid, dashed or dotted curves in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset

).
 (b)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

All these curves meet at their endpoints, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,s^{2m})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(s^{2m},1)$
\end_inset

.
 (c)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

At the endpoints the curves become tangent to the vertical and horizontal
 lines
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}=1$
\end_inset

 respectively, provided
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\not=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%This is due to the square root $
\backslash
sqrt{p_1p_2}$ in Eq.~(
\backslash
ref{unit cond}).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%A more detailed analysis shows that f
\end_layout

\end_inset

(d)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 the curve 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%defined by Eq.~(
\backslash
ref{unit cond}) 
\end_layout

\end_inset

is an arc of the hyperbola 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}=s^{2m}$
\end_inset

 (dashed line in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset

).
 (e)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Each of these curves and the segments joining their end points with the
 vertex
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

 are the boundary of the sets (any of the gray regions in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{\alpha}=\{(q_{1},q_{2}):\sqrt{p_{1}p_{2}}\,s^{n}\alpha+\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}-s^{m}\ge0\}.\label{S_alpha}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

They satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\alpha}\subset S_{\alpha'}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha<\alpha'$
\end_inset

.
 (f)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Moreover, the sets
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $S_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 are convex if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\ge0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%For $
\backslash
alpha
\backslash
ge0$ the set $S_
\backslash
alpha$ is convex, as follows from the observation that~$(xy)^{1/2}$ is a
 concave function of its two (non-negative) arguments~$x$ and~$y$.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this point a geometrical picture of the optimization problem emerges
 (See Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset

).
 Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) defines a straight segment on the square 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le q_{i}\le1$
\end_inset

 with a normal vector in the first quadrant parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1},\eta_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 For fixed a-priori probabilities, the average failure probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the distance from this segment to the origin
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 is convex and the stretch of its boundary given by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

 is smooth, a unique point 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{1},q_{2})$
\end_inset

 of tangency with the segment
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) exists for any value of the priors and finite 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 It gives 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 and defines the optimal cloning strategy.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%(See Fig.~
\backslash
ref{fig:1}).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note in passing that the inclusion hierarchy of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 provides a simple geometrical proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{1}\rangle=|\alpha_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, is indeed the optimal choice.
 On the other hand, we recall that for cloning by discrimination we have
 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\alpha_{1}|\alpha_{2}\rangle=\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 (or
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}=0$
\end_inset

).
 From points
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(b) and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(c) above, it follows that for any finite 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and arbitrary priors 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 this protocol is strictly suboptimal, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}<Q_{{\rm UD}}$
\end_inset

, where the subscript UD is a reminder that the failure rate of cloning
 by discrimination is that of UD.
 One could say that optimal cloning is incompatible with discerning the
 identity of the input states for any finite number of clones.
 However, optimal cloning and UD become one and the same in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{n}\to0$
\end_inset

 and the curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) collapses to the hyperbola 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}=s^{2m}$
\end_inset

, as it does for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

.
 We will come back to this point below.
 A more quantitative analysis requires finding a convenient parametrization
 of the curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

).
 To this end, simpler and more manageable expressions are derived if the
 symmetry under 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\leftrightarrow q_{2}$
\end_inset

 is preserved.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{q_{i}}=\sin\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\theta_{i}\leq\pi/2$
\end_inset

.
 By further introducing the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\cos(\theta_{1}+\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\cos(\theta_{1}-\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 we manage to linearize the constraint
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

), which now reads as 
\begin_inset Formula $2s^{m}=(1+s^{n})y-(1-s^{n})x$
\end_inset

.
 A natural parametrization for this straight line is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=\frac{1-(1+s^{n})t}{s^{n-m}},\qquad y=\frac{1-(1-s^{n})t}{s^{n-m}},\label{x & y}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where again we have taken the most symmetrical choice.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%s^m=-{1-s^n
\backslash
over 2}x+{1+s^n
\backslash
over2}y;
\backslash
quad -1
\backslash
le x, y
\backslash
le 1.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Because of the symmetry of this procedure, the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\leftrightarrow q_{2}$
\end_inset

 (equivalently, under 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}\leftrightarrow\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, the two mirror halves of the curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) under this transformation are mapped into the same straight line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "x & y"

\end_inset

).
 By expressing 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 as a function of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 only half of the original curve is recovered.
 The other half is trivially obtained by applying
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\leftrightarrow q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The allowed domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "x & y"

\end_inset

) follows from that of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, readily seen from their definition to be the region 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|\le y\le1$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1-s^{n-m}}{1-s^{n}}\le t\le1.\label{range t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

After putting the various pieces together 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%q_i=
\backslash
sin^2
\backslash
!
\backslash
left
\backslash
{{
\backslash
arccos{x}-(-1)^i
\backslash
arccos{y}
\backslash
over2}
\backslash
right
\backslash
},
\backslash
quad i=1,2.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
label{par trig}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{equation}
\end_layout

\end_inset

one can easily get rid of the trigonometric functions and express Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) in parametric form as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{i}=\frac{1-xy-(-1)^{i}\sqrt{1-x^{2}}\sqrt{1-y^{2}}}{2},\quad i=1,2.\label{par sqrt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%where we recall that $x$ and $y$ are defined in Eq.~(
\backslash
ref{x & y}) with the range of $t$ given in Eq.~(
\backslash
ref{range t}).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2"

\end_inset

 shows examples of the unitary curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) for (a)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 and (b)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n=5$
\end_inset

.
 In both cases 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

.
 For larger 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 the curves closely approximate the hyperbolae 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}=s^{2m}$
\end_inset

 (dashed lines) for small and moderate values of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, while for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 close to one the hyperbolas remain closer to the vertex
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

, but still retain the same end points.
 As mentioned previously, in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 all curves become hyperbolic.
 
