\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can return to the minimization of the average failure probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Despite the apparent simplicity of the problem, finding the minimum 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 as an explicit function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

 involves solving a quartic equation without a simple form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using the alternative change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\sqrt{q_{1}q_{2}}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $v=(q_{1}+q_{2})/2$
\end_inset

, the unitary constraint, Eq
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

), defines a parabola on the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

-
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 plane.
 Likewise, the failure rate, Eq
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

), defines an ellipse with center on the 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 axis whose eccentricity only depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The size of the ellipse and the 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 coordinate of its center both increase with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 emerges when the ellipse is tangent to the parabola.
 The intersection of these two conics can be written as a quartic equation.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Another geometrical interpretation of optimality emerges:  for a fixed
 value of the overlap and number of clones, the parabola remains constant.
  For an increased a priori probability $
\backslash
eta_1$ the ellipse inflates, and its height increases proportionally to
 the total failure rate Q.
  The optimal value of Q emerges when the ellipse just touches the parabola,
 implying a double root.
  The intersection of these two conics can be written as a fourth degree
 equation.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Instead, we will derive the parametric equation of the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1},Q_{{\rm min}})$
\end_inset

.
 This, along with our complete description of the unitary curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

), provides a full account of the solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Without any loss of generality we may assume that
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\le\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, or equivalently, that
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $0\le\eta_{1}\le1/2$
\end_inset

.
 Then the slope of the vector normal to the straight line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) is less or equal to one and thus it can only become tangent to the lower
 half of the unitary curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) (see Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%It is apparent from Fig.~
\backslash
ref{fig:2} that 
\end_layout

\end_inset

The slope of this lower half increases monotonically as we move away from
 the line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{2}$
\end_inset

, where it has the value
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, and vanishes before we reach the line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from the properties (a)--(f) above and can be checked using
 Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par sqrt"

\end_inset

).
 The values of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 at which the slope is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 are respectively 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{-1}=\frac{1-s^{n-m}}{1-s^{n}},\quad t_{0}=\frac{1-s^{2(n-m)}}{1-s^{2n}},\label{t's}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we note that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the lower value of the range of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "range t"

\end_inset

).
 For any point 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{1}(t),q_{2}(t))$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[t_{-1},t_{0}]$
\end_inset

 there is a line 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=\eta_{1}q_{1}+\eta_{2}q_{2}$
\end_inset

 that is tangent to it, starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=1/2$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{-1}$
\end_inset

 up to 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This observation enables us to derive the desired parametric expression
 for the optimality curve
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1},Q_{{\rm min}})$
\end_inset

 as follows: for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in the range above, a necessary condition for tangency is 
\begin_inset Box Frameless
position "c"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "c"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 1
width ""
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}q'_{1}+\eta_{2}q'_{2}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $q'_{i}=dq_{i}/dt$
\end_inset

.
 In this equation we can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

) using that
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 By substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) with
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par sqrt"

\end_inset

) we enforce contact with the unitarity curve and obtain the expression
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

.
 The final result can be cast as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\eta_{1}=\frac{q'_{2}}{q'_{2}-q'_{1}},\;\;Q_{{\rm min}}=\frac{q'_{2}q_{1}-q'_{1}q_{2}}{q'_{2}-q'_{1}},\;\;t_{-1}\le t\le t_{0},\label{main}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 are given in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "t's"

\end_inset

) and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par sqrt"

\end_inset

).
 The expressions for the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $q'_{i}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%most easily derived from the trigonometric form~(
\backslash
ref{par trig}) to be
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q'_{i}=\frac{\sqrt{q_{i}(1-q_{i})}}{s^{n-m}}\left\{ \frac{1+s^{n}}{\sqrt{1-x^{2}}}-(-1)^{i}\frac{1-s^{n}}{\sqrt{1-y^{2}}}\right\} .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:3"

\end_inset

 shows plots of the curves 
\begin_inset Formula $(\eta_{1},Q_{{\rm min}})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 input copies and (a) 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 or (b) 
\begin_inset Formula $n=5$
\end_inset

 clones, as in the previous figure.
 We see that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 is an increasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 in the given range 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1/2]$
\end_inset

.
 The values of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 at the end points of this range follow by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{-1}$
\end_inset

, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "t's"

\end_inset

), into Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par sqrt"

\end_inset

).
 They are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{0}=q_{2}(t_{0})=\frac{s^{2m}-s^{2n}}{1-s^{2n}},\quad Q_{-1}=\frac{s^{m}-s^{n}}{1-s^{n}},\label{Q's}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}=Q_{-1}$
\end_inset

 holds for equal priors and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}=Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\to0$
\end_inset

 (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}\to1$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\begin{array}{c}
\includegraphics[width=26.7em]{Fig_{3}NC.pdf}\end{array}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Minimum cloning failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 (solid lines) and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

UD failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm UD}}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 (dashed lines) for the same values of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 used in the previous figure.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:3"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset

The dashed lines in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:3"

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(b) are the well known piecewise unambiguous discrimination solution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bergou"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{{\rm UD}}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
\eta_{1}+s^{2m}\eta_{2},\quad & {\displaystyle 0\le\eta_{1}\le\frac{s^{2m}}{1+s^{2m}};}\\[0.5em]
2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\,s^{m}, & {\displaystyle \frac{s^{2m}}{1+s^{2m}}\le\eta_{1}\le\frac{1}{2}.}
\end{array}\right.\label{UD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is apparent from these plots that the optimal cloning protocol performs
 strictly better than cloning by discrimination, as was proved above.
 However, as the number of produced clones becomes larger the difference
 in performance reduces.
 In Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:3"

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(b), for only 
\begin_inset Formula $n=5$
\end_inset

, a difference is hardly noticeable for 
\begin_inset Formula $s\le0.5$
\end_inset

.
 For larger overlaps it takes larger values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 to get the same level of agreement.
 As discussed above, in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

 there is perfect agreement for any 
\begin_inset Formula $s<1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The complete UD solution in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

) emerges naturally from our geometrical approach in a straightforward manner:
 First, we recall that in this case the right hand side of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}=s^{2m}$
\end_inset

 (dashed lines in Figs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:1"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:2"

\end_inset

).
 The maximum slopes of these curves are at their end points and all have
 the value
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $-s^{2m}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 has a cusp at 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,s^{2m})$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that a unique point of tangency with the line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) exists for 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2m}<\eta_{1}/\eta_{2}\le1$
\end_inset

 (recall that we are assuming
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\le1/2$
\end_inset

).
 This condition gives the 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 interval for that solution.
 The tangency condition, 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{2},q_{1})\propto(\eta_{1},\eta_{2})$
\end_inset

, quickly leads us to the optimal failure rate in the second line of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

).
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2m}>\eta_{1}/\eta_{2}\ge0$
\end_inset

 tangency is not possible, and the optimal line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) merely touches the cusp on the boundary of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

, so the expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 becomes the first line of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

).
 In geometrical terms, the straight line
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "obj fun"

\end_inset

) pivots on the end point as 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 varies between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2m}/(1+s^{2m})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the second case in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

), one has 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1},p_{1}\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and there are three orthogonal flag states in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Ui"

\end_inset

), namely, the two success states 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{1}\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, and the failure state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $|\Phi\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-outcome measurement can be represented by a 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-element positive operator valued measure (POVM) on 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathscr{H}}^{\otimes m}$
\end_inset

.
 For the first line in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}=1-q_{1}=0$
\end_inset

, which leads to a 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

-outcome projective measurement, as only one success flag state (
\begin_inset Formula $|\alpha_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

) is needed in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Ui"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This two-paragraph derivation of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

) proves that the convergence of the optimal cloning failure probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}$
\end_inset

 to that of cloning by discrimination, with rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm UD}}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

), follows from the convergence of the general unitarity curve in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "unit cond"

\end_inset

) to the hyperbola 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}q_{2}=s^{2m}$
\end_inset

, i.e., from 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\alpha\to0}S_{\alpha}=S_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Interestingly enough, such convergence entails a phenomenon analogous to
 a second order phase transition.
 Our geometrical approach shows that the average failure probability 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm min}}(\eta_{1})$
\end_inset

 is an infinitely differentiable function of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 for finite 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 However, as 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 goes to infinity (or at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

, for the sake of this discussion) the limiting function 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm UD}}(\eta_{1})$
\end_inset

 has a discontinuous second derivative.
 Moreover, the symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}\leftrightarrow q_{2}$
\end_inset

 breaks in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

phase" corresponding to the first line in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

).
 A
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

similar phenomenon arises in UD of more than two pure states
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bergou1"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%It has been argued above that cloning by discrimination is strictly suboptimal
 (unless $n
\backslash
to 
\backslash
infty$).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%One could likewise wonder if discrimination by cloning can be optimal.
 On heuristic grounds, one should not expect this to be so, as cloning involves
 a measurement and some information can be drawn from the observed outcome.
 However, the equal-prior and the $
\backslash
eta_1
\backslash
to 0$ cases provide remarkable exceptions: for $
\backslash
eta_1 = 
\backslash
eta_2= 1/2$, cloning succeeds with probability $P=1-Q_{-1}$, in which case
 the produced $n$-clone states are equally likely.
 The UD of these estates fails with probability $s^{n}$, as follows from
 Eq.~(
\backslash
ref{UD}) applied to $n$ copies.
 The total failure probability is then $Q_{-1}+P s^n=s^m$, which is the
 optimal UD failure rate of the original input states, Eq.~(
\backslash
ref{UD}).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%If  $
\backslash
eta_1
\backslash
to 0$ then $P=1-Q_{0}$, and only $|
\backslash
psi^n_2
\backslash
rangle$ is produced with non-vanishing probability.
 Failure in the second step (UD) is given by Eq.~(
\backslash
ref{UD}) applied to $n$ copies.
 The total failure rate is $Q_{0}+P s^{2n}=s^{2m}$, also achieving optimality.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has been argued above that cloning by discrimination is strictly suboptimal
 (unless 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

).
 One could likewise wonder if discrimination by cloning can be optimal.
 On heuristic grounds, one should not expect this to be so, as cloning involves
 a measurement and some information can be drawn from the observed outcome.
 However, the equal-prior and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\to0$
\end_inset

 cases provide remarkable exceptions.
 For both we may write the total failure rate as 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm C}}+(1-Q_{{\rm C}})Q_{{\rm UD}}$
\end_inset

, where C stands for cloning.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}=\eta_{2}=1/2$
\end_inset

, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Q's"

\end_inset

) implies 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm C}}=Q_{-1}$
\end_inset

, in which case the produced 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-clone states are equally likely.
 The UD of these states fails with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{n}$
\end_inset

, as follows from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

) applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 copies.
 The total failure rate is then 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{m}$
\end_inset

, which is the optimal UD failure rate of the original input states, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

).
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}\to0$
\end_inset

 then only 
\begin_inset Formula $|\psi_{2}^{n}\rangle$
\end_inset

 is produced with non-vanishing probability and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm C}}=Q_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Failure in the second step (UD) is given by the top line in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "UD"

\end_inset

) applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 copies.
 The total failure rate is 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{2m}$
\end_inset

, also achieving optimality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using our main result in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "main"

\end_inset

), and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par sqrt"

\end_inset

) one can check that these are the only cases where discrimination by cloning
 is optimal.
 These are also the only cases where no information gain can be drawn from
 the cloning measurement.
 This hints at how special these cases are and justifies the need of the
 derived solution for arbitrary priors to have a full account of two-state
 cloning.
\end_layout

